\begin{eqnarray}
P = iQ
\begin{bmatrix}
0  & -1     &       &        &      &   \\
1  & 0 & \ddots & \ddots &        &  \\
  &        & \ddots & \ddots & 0 & -1 \\
 &       &        &      & 1      & 0
\end{bmatrix}
Q^{T},
\end{eqnarray}

where $Q$ is the matrix whose columns are composed alternatively of the real and imaginary parts of the eigenvectors of the Majorana Hamiltonian. 
The eigenvalues $\lambda_1,...,\lambda_i,...\lambda_N$ of $\tilde{P} \subset P$ lie between $[-1,1]$, where $\tilde{P}$ denotes the correlation matrix restricted to the subsystem and 
$N$ denotes the total number of the sites inside the subsystem; then the eigenvalues of the reduced density matrix can be written as \cite{calabrese-2010,vidal-2004},

\begin{eqnarray}
\Gamma(s_1,...s_i,...s_N)= \prod_{i=1,N} \frac{1+ s_i \lambda_i}{2}
\label{density-eigvl}
\end{eqnarray}

$s_i$ can take values $\pm 1$ and thus we obtain in total $2^N$ eigenvalues of the density matrix. The von-Neumann entanglement entropy is thus given by ~\cite{yao-qi2010},
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{final-ent}
S_A = \sum \frac{1+ \lambda_i}{2} {\rm log} \frac{1+ \lambda_i}{2} + \frac{1- \lambda_i}{2} {\rm log} \frac{1- \lambda_i}{2} 
\end{eqnarray}  

Entanglement gap or Schmidt gap is another useful quantity to characterize the entanglement properties and in particular has been conjectured to detect topological order 
\cite{haldane-2008} and phase transitions \cite{konik-2013}.
 The entanglement gap may be defined as ~\cite{haldane-2008, konik-2013}
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta_A= - (\rm{log} \Gamma_M - \rm{log} \Gamma_M^{\prime}),
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Gamma_M$ and $\Gamma_M^{\prime} $ are the largest and the second largest eigenvalues of the density matrix.

From Eq. (\ref{density-eigvl}), it is clear that the $\Gamma_M$ is obtained when the contribution $\frac{1+ s_i \lambda_i}{2}$ 
is maximized i.e one has to consider the contribution $\textrm{Max} \Big(\frac{1+ \lambda_i}{2}, \frac{1- \lambda_i}{2}\Big)$ for a 
given $\lambda_i$. The second largest eigenvalue is obtained by changing  $(1+ \lambda)/2$ to $(1-\lambda)/2$ for the  smallest 
value of $|\lambda|$. With this, entanglement gap can be simplified to
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{final-gap}
\Delta_A= {\rm log} \frac{(1+ |\lambda|_{min})}{(1- |\lambda|_{min})} 
\end{eqnarray}
We evaluate the quantities given by Eq. (\ref{final-ent}) and Eq.(\ref{final-gap}) numerically and discuss the results 
in Sec.\ref{section-2}. \\

